<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
V. Health/Medical Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should integrate occupant protection into health programs. The failure of drivers and passengers to use
occupant protection systems is a major health problem that must be recognized by the health care community. The SHSA
and the State Health Department should collaborate in developing programs that: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Integrate occupant protection into professional health training curricula and comprehensive public health planning;

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Promote occupant protection systems as a health promotion/disease prevention measure; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Require public health and medical personnel to use available motor vehicle occupant protection systems when on the
job; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Provide technical assistance and education about the importance of motor vehicle occupant protection to primary
caregivers, (e.g., doctors, nurses, clinic staff); 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Include questions about safety belt use in health risk appraisals; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Utilize health care providers as visible public spokespersons for belt use and child safety seat use; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Provide information about availability of child safety seats through maternity hospitals and other pre-natal and
natal care centers (see Program Component VI: Child Passenger Safety Program); and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Collect, analyze, and publicize data on additional injuries and medical expenses resulting from non-use of occupant
protection devices. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VI. Child Passenger Safety Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should vigorously promote the use of child safety seats. States should require every child up to 40 pounds
to ride correctly secured in a child safety seat that meets Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards (see Program Component
II: Legislation, Regulation, and Policy). State and community child passenger safety programs that will help to
achieve that objective should be established to: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Educate parents, pediatricians, hospitals, law enforcement, EMS and the general public about the safety risks to
small children, the benefits of child safety seats, and their responsibilities for compliance with child passenger
safety laws; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Encourage child safety seat retailers and auto dealers to provide information about child seat and vehicle compatibility,
as well as correct use; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Require safe child transportation policies for certification of pre-school and day care providers; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Require hospitals to ensure that newborn and other small children are correctly secured in an approved child safety
seat or safety belt upon discharge; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Make child safety seats available at affordable cost to low-income families; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Encourage local law enforcement to vigorously enforce child passenger safety laws, including safety belt use laws
as they apply to children. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VII. School-Based Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should incorporate occupant protection education in school curricula. Buckling up is a good health habit
and, like other health habits, must be taught at an early age and reinforced until the habit is well established. The
State Department of Education and the State Highway Safety Agency should: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Ensure that highway safety in general, and occupant protection in particular, are included in the State-approved
K&hyph;12 health and safety education curricula and textbooks; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Establish and enforce written policies requiring that school employees operating a motor vehicle on the job use safety
belts; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Encourage active promotion of regular safety belt use through classroom and extra-curricular activities as well
as in the school-based health clinics. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
VIII. Worksite Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should encourage all employers to require safety belt use on the job as a condition of employment. The Federal
government has already taken that step for its employees. Private sector employers should follow the lead of Federal
and State government employers and comply with all applicable FHWA Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulations or Occupational
Health and Safety (OSHA) regulations requiring private business employees to use safety belts on the job. All employers
should: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Establish and enforce a safety belt use policy with sanctions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Conduct occupant protection education programs for employees on their belt use policies and the safety benefits
of motor vehicle occupant protection. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
IX. Outreach Program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should encourage extensive community involvement in occupant protection education by involving individuals
and organizations outside the traditional highway safety community. Community involvement broadens public support
for the State's programs and can increase a State's ability to deliver highway safety education programs. To encourage
community involvement, States should: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940114-1-00051 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940114-1-00008 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Establish a coalition or task force of individuals and organizations to actively promote use of occupant protection
systems;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Create an effective communications network among coalition members to keep members informed; and
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Provide materials and resources necessary to conduct occupant protection education programs, especially directed
toward young people, in local settings.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
X. Evaluation Program
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State should conduct several different types of evaluation to effectively measure progress and to plan and implement
new program strategies. Program management should:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Conduct and publicize at least one statewide observational survey of safety belt and child safety seat use annually,
making every effort to ensure that it meets applicable federal guidelines;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Maintain trend data on child safety seat and belt use in fatal crashes;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Identify target populations through observational surveys and crash statistics;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Conduct and publicize statewide surveys of public knowledge and attitudes about occupant protection laws and systems;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Obtain monthly or quarterly data from law enforcement agencies on the number of safety belt and child passenger safety
citations and convictions;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Evaluate the use of program resources and the effectiveness of existing general public and target population education
programs;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Obtain data on morbidity as well as the estimated cost of crashes in regards to safety belt usage and non-usage; and
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Ensure that evaluation results are an integral part of new program planning and problem identification.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=74 g=1 f=1 -->
Highway Safety Program Guideline
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
No. 21
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Roadway Safety
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Each State, in cooperation with its political subdivisions, should have a comprehensive roadway safety program
that is directed toward reducing the number and severity of traffic crashes.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
I. Program Management
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) provides administrative oversight for the Roadway Safety portion of
the section 402 highway safety program in close coordination with the State Highway Safety Agency (SHSA) and the State
Highway Agency (SHA). Although section 402 dollars cannot be utilized for highway construction, maintenance or
design activities, they can be used to develop and implement systems and procedures for carrying out safety construction
and operational improvements. These funds can also be used to augment Federal-aid highway programs, such as the Hazard
Elimination Program (Section 152) and the Rail-Highway Crossings Programs (Section 130), as well as other safety
construction activities.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
An effective Roadway Safety program is based on sound analyses of roadway-related crash information and applies
engineering principles in identifying highway design or operational improvements that will address the crash problem.
The SHSA should:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Assign program staff to work directly with the FHWA division safety engineer on roadway-related safety programs.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
