<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In general, participants at the regional meetings and the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
negotiations recognized that grounds for cancellation of a loan 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
obligation under section 437 of the HEA should include a case 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
where a student was unable to obtain employment after attending 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the school, and the school had falsely certified that the student 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
had the ability to benefit from the school's training. This kind 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of falsification is both part of the loan certification process 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and results in a student being left without needed skills. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Therefore, the proposed regulations focus on the school's false 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
representation that the student had the ability to benefit as the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
grounds for cancellation under this new provision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The statute and regulations have addressed the ability-to-benefit requirement for many years, and the proposed
regulations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reflect both the legal elements of that requirement and some 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
enforcement perspectives developed in implementing it. For 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
example, the school has always been required to test the ability 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to benefit only of those applicants who did not have a high 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school diploma, and the school therefore does not certify 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
anything regarding the ability to benefit of high school 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
graduates. Since 1987, students who had a general education 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
diploma, or obtained one after enrolling, and students who lacked 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
both a GED and a high school diploma but completed an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institutionally prescribed remedial education program, have been 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
deemed by Congress to have the ability to benefit, and the rule 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would incorporate that congressional judgement. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The regulations therefore would generally permit relief in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the case of a student whom the school was required to test for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ability to benefit, but either failed to test at all, or tested 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in disregard of the requirements for proper use of the test 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
adopted. Schools have a continuing legal obligation to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
administer tests, subject to criteria developed by the school's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
accreditor, in compliance with test protocols. These criteria 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and protocols may include requirements related both to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
accuracy of the test results as to the individual tested and to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the continuing development and validation of the test mechanism. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Non-compliance with testing requirements may warrant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
administrative sanctions against the school, but a false 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
certification claim under this provision requires the Department 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to determine a different question. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A false certification claim depends not on whether the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school met all its obligations with regard to testing, but on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
whether a test already given lacks credibility as a measure of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the student's ability to benefit so that the Department should, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the absence of other evidence, regard the student as lacking 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that ability. The Secretary expects that practical, specific 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standards will be needed to help identify those deviations from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
testing requirements that support an inference that the student 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
lacked ability to benefit. For example, use of photocopied 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
versions of tests by the school or test administrator may violate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the requirements of the test publisher, but may have no direct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effect on the accuracy of the assessment of the student's ability 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to benefit. Use of an indefensibly low cutoff score by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school on an ability-to-benefit test does not discredit an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assessment of the ability of those students who score above a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
legitimate cutoff score, such as those now published by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary. Similarly, minor deviations from required time limits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
may have little effect on the validity of the test results. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary intends to address these practical considerations in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the final regulations, and invites public comment on the content 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of those standards or guidelines. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In applying these standards, moreover, the Secretary has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consistently recognized that a student may actually have the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ability to benefit from the school's training even though the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school does not test that student's ability or does so 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
improperly. The proposed regulations therefore recognize that a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
student who actually obtains employment in the occupation for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which the school's program was designed to prepare him or her had 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the actual ability to benefit from that training without regard 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to whether the school falsified its test of ability to benefit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A student not properly tested for ability to benefit who 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
nevertheless completes the program of instruction can reasonably 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be considered to have found the training consistent with his or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
her aptitude, and the proposed regulations would provide for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cancellation only if the a student had unsuccessfully tried to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
find employment in the occupation for which the program was 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designed to prepare him or her. Conversely, a student not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
properly tested who withdraws from the course can be reasonably 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regarded as having found the training not consistent with his or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
her aptitude, and the proposed regulations grant relief to this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
kind of student (or a parent PLUS borrower who borrowed on behalf 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the student) unless the student actually obtained employment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in that occupation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
