<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
By allowing a filing of a claim on the date ``collection of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the loan is stayed''_the date of the filing of the petition by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the borrower, or, in a Chapter 13 case, by the endorser or the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
borrower_rather than the date a borrower receives a discharge, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the statute might be read to permit claims to be submitted if an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
endorser files, rather than, as under prior law, only in borrower 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bankruptcies. Nothing in the amendments suggested that such a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result was intended, and the proposed regulations would permit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the submission of a bankruptcy claim only in the case of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
borrower bankruptcy. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The proposed regulations would continue to require lenders 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to file proofs of claim in the bankruptcy proceeding, unless the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
guaranty agency directs otherwise or the holder is officially 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
notified by the court that no assets are available for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
distribution. If the guaranty agency later receives notice that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assets have become available, the guarantor must file a proof of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
claim at that point. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Participants in the negotiated rulemaking proceedings noted 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that a growing number of discharges were being received by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
borrowers who file sequential bankruptcy petitions, particularly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
those who first file for relief in Chapter 13. During the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pendency of the prior bankruptcy case, loans in repayment less 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
than seven years are non-dischargeable without proof of undue 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hardship, yet cannot be enforced by the holder according to their 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
original terms; little or nothing may be paid on those loans 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
during the proceeding. Rather than attempting to show that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
repayment would constitute an undue hardship, or negotiating an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
income-sensitive repayment arrangement with the holder, borrowers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
who complete their Chapter 13 proceeding may then file a second 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bankruptcy petition, making sure that the second is filed more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
than seven years after the loan entered repayment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Bankruptcy Code excludes the period of ``any applicable 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
suspension of the repayment period'' from the seven-year period 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
during which loans are dischargeable only for undue hardship. 11 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
U.S.C. 523(a)(8)(A). If the term ``suspension of the repayment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
period'' is read, as these borrowers contend, to include only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
forbearance or deferments granted by the holder of the loan, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reality of the forbearance imposed by virtue of the automatic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
stay in the prior bankruptcy_which barred enforcement of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
loan according to its terms during the pendency of the bankruptcy_would be ignored, and borrowers who have neither
made the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
required seven-year attempt to repay nor demonstrated undue 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hardship would obtain a discharge in the second bankruptcy. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary does not consider this interpretation of the statute to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be consistent with its purpose, and the only court that has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
addressed this precise issue has concluded that the period during 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which enforcement of a loan is stayed in a prior bankruptcy is an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``applicable suspension of the repayment period'' for purposes of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
computing the seven-year period for a subsequent bankruptcy. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
re Saburah,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 136 B.R. 246, 254 (Bankr. C.D. Cal. 1992). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In light of the above discussion, the Secretary proposes to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interpret the term ``applicable suspension of the repayment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
period'' to include periods during which the automatic stay in a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bankruptcy proceeding is in effect. The Secretary further 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recognizes that a borrower who in fact meets his or her 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
obligation under the original repayment agreement during the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bankruptcy has acted in a manner consistent with the intent of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the statute, and this proposed interpretation would not regard 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the period of the first bankruptcy as a period of suspension of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
repayment for the borrower. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The death and bankruptcy requirements in proposed &sect;682.402 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are taken directly from the HEA. There is no change to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
current disability cancellation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Closed School Cancellations
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The closed school cancellation provision is taken, in large 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
part, directly from the mandates of the HEA, although the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed regulations reflect some areas of necessary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interpretation. The discussion that follows is grouped into 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
three major areas where the Secretary and the negotiators had 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
discretion to interpret the statutory closed school cancellation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provision: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Student Withdrawal Prior to the Closing of the School
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
There was unanimous agreement among the negotiators and the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary that it would be inequitable to strictly limit a closed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school cancellation to only those students who were in attendance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at the school on the date that the school officially closed. As 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
discussed earlier, conditions at the school immediately preceding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
its closing may have caused a deterioration in the educational 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
program that would have prompted a student to withdraw. Such a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
student should not lose entitlement to a loan cancellation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
because of his or her prescience or inability to tolerate the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school's deterioration. To balance the interests of students and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the federal taxpayers (who ultimately must pay the cost of each 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cancelled loan), the Secretary proposes to limit this withdrawal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
period to not more than 90 days prior to the date the school 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
closed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
2. Student Use of Teach-out or Transfer of Academic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Credits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
As discussed earlier, the Secretary does not believe that a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
student who completed the educational program for which the loan 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
was intended, even though the completion occurred through a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
teach-out at another school or by the student's transfer of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
academic credits earned at the closed school, should be able to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
avoid repaying that loan. The student is not required to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
transfer those credits or make use of a teach-out opportunity, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
but if the student chooses to do so, then the Secretary believes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that, because the student was able to complete the educational 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
program, it would be unfair to require the Federal taxpayer to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pay the student's loan. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
3. Student Statement Requirement
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Secretary believes that a statement made by the student 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under penalty of perjury demonstrating eligibility for a closed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
school discharge should be obtained from the student to assist 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Secretary or the Secretary's designees in pursuing claims 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
against the closed school. Without this statement, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary's ability to protect the interests of the Federal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
taxpayer would be frustrated. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

